nt||HT|e|cs|1|cp|4|fp||at|
^-{    SPOTTING A DANGER SIGNAL    }
^-|
CS||CP||fp||AT|^B@2^Y@3T|FP||AT|he most usual danger signal is the presence of some long, almost solid suit in the Dummy. When you see a suit of this kind you must realize at once that you will not have time to reduce the Declarer's trump holding to your own level. The chances are that a force will simply give the Declarer more time to establish his suit and discard his losers. Consequently you must attack without hesitation and hope for the best.|PG||AT|

The following deal shows how a danger signal may be spotted:|PG||NT||
%%%%%%%%%%%%% Board 3
pn|,You,,|st||SK|W|md|1SQ2HAKQT2DA62CJ83,SAKJT4H76D985CT94,S753HJ43DKQJ43CK6,S986H985DT7CAQ752|RH||AH|Board 3|mb|4H|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|pc|sK|pc|s3|NT|^B@2
You are West, and open the spade King against South's contract of four hearts.|PG||AT| Your Partner plays the six-spot,|pc|s6|PG||AT|^*B and, as soon as you see Declarer's deuce,|pc|s2|pg||at| you know that the six is a discouraging signal (because you know the whereabouts of all lower cards).^*N|pg||NT|^B@2
Therefore, you may as well lead the spade Ace,|pc|sA|PG||AT| for if Partner holds three spades, the Declarer's Queen must fall.|pc|s5|pc|s8|pc|sQ|PG||AT| This happens, and at the third trick you are confronted with a chance to force the Declarer to ruff a third round of spades. Certainly such a play will not directly forfeit a trick, but at the same time you should be restrained from making it by the presence of the five-card diamond suit in the Dummy.|PG||NT|^B@2
It should be apparent that if the Declarer has a solid heart suit plus the diamond Ace, he can run off enough tricks for his game contract before you can intercede. If Partner holds the diamond Ace, he will be sure to take it at a later time, and the fact that the suit is not led immediately will make no difference. The only suit left is clubs—and you must lead a club at the third trick.|PG||SK||NT|^B@2
You select the Ten—top of your tripleton—and, regardless of what Dummy plays, Partner must make both his Ace and Queen. If you had gone on with a third round of spades, the Declarer would have ruffed, it is true, but he would then have drawn the remaining trumps, taken his five diamonds, and scored his 10 tricks for game. The lead of a club at the third trick is your only way of stopping the game.|PG||pc|cT|pc|c6|pc|cQ|pc|c3|pg||
