CS||CP||fp||AT|^B@2^Y@3A|FP||AT|nother variation of the force on Declarer occurs when the Defending Side is faced with the problem of preventing a Declarer from obtaining discards in Dummy. |cp|8|at|As a general rule, it is safe to say that a player should always ruff, even though he knows that he is going to be over-ruffed|cp||at|. The trump sacrificed can be of little use and if the Declarer over-ruffs he is forced to retain whatever loser he is trying to get rid of. The following hand illustrates this principle:|PG||NT||
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Board 7
pn||st||md|1SKQJT3HA86DA82CA5,S54HKQJDQT5CJ9832,S9862H973D76CKQ64,SA7HT542DKJ943CT7|RH||AH|Board 7|mb|4S|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|NT|^B@2
You are sitting East and South is the Declarer at a contract of four spades.|PG||pc|hK|pc|h3|pc|h4|pc|hA|at|^*B West opens the King of hearts and Declarer wins with the Ace.^*N|PG||cp||at| He can not afford to draw trumps immediately as then he will automatically lose 4 tricks. So he therefore leads three rounds of clubs in the hope of getting rid of one of his heart losers.|PG||cp||pc|cA|pc|c2|pc|c4|pc|c7|pg||
pc|c5|pc|c3|pc|cK|pc|cT|pg||
pc|cQ|pc|s7|NT|^B@2
On the third round of clubs you must ruff with the seven of spades and, from this point on, Declarer is helpless. He can either over-ruff or take his discard as he chooses, but nothing can prevent him from losing a total of 4 tricks.|PG||mc|9|pg||NT|^B@2
Note that it makes a great deal of difference whether you ruff with the Ace or with the seven. If you ruff with the Ace, Declarer will simply discard his heart and will succeed in getting rid of two losers on 1 trick. If your holding were Ten-seven or Jack-seven, or even Queen-seven, however, you should prefer to ruff with the higher card, as this may develop a trick in partner's hand (|fp|2|cp|8|at|*|FP||CP||AT|).|PG||cp|8|at|

*|CP||at|^*I Umpteen years later this specific type of play was christened "the uppercut" by various and sundry experts.—S. Fry. Jr.^*N|PG||NT|^B@2
This is true even if you hold three cards headed by the Ten or Jack. With three cards headed by the Queen the situation is a little closer, as you may conceivably be giving up a trick by ruffing high. Your choice depends on your chance of obtaining a trick with that Queen later. |PG||NT|^B@2
However, do not make the mistake of thinking that you should preserve the Queen and the small cards too, for it is almost always better to use one of your trumps. Even if you sacrifice a possible trump trick, you are at least preventing the Declarer from obtaining a much-needed discard.|PG||HT|v|AT|@D@D Please click the forward arrow to play this hand double dummy.|PG||PF|y|NT||
